<DOC><DOCNO> AP890724-0066 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1137EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Madagascar     07-24 0326</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Madagascar,0340</SECOND><HEAD>Radio Station Seized in Coup Claim, But Government Asserts Control</HEAD><DATELINE>ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Six armed men took over astate-run radio station today and announced the government'soverthrow, but authorities quickly denied that a coup had occurredand asserted they were in control.   Apart from the seizure of the radio station, there were noreports of violence. No injuries were reported at the station.   In Antananarivo, the capital of this island off East Africa,people went about their business as usual. The nation has about 10million people.   The armed men took over the station of Madagascar national radioearly today and broadcast a statement claiming the government ofPresident Didier Ratsiraka had been replaced. It said the countrywas now being ruled by a group of opposition political leaders.   Ratsiraka was in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, attending a summit ofthe Organization of African Unity. It was not immediately possibleto determine if he intended to remain there.   Two hours after the men seized the station, Information MinisterSimon Pierre broadcast a government message on national radio. Hedenied that a coup had taken place and called for calm.   That message, which was broadcast several times during themorning, said an investigation was under way but provided no otherdetails.   A later newscast said one of the armed men had been identified,but that the other men had worn masks. It was not immediately knownif the men had been arrested.   In April, three people died and about 73 were injured in clasheswith police after Ratsiraka's re-election.   Opposition leaders said the elections were riddled with fraudand called for the formation of a provisional government. They saidit should include representatives of the military, students andchurches and should yield power after new elections.   Ratsiraka, initially chosen to rule by the military in 1975, wasre-elected to a third seven-year term on March 12 with about 62percent of the vote.</TEXT></DOC>